{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565763"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:31:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:31:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18452"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18452"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.18,0.01,0.02,0.68]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11181"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74866"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11181"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18452"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60372"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"45"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11641"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25937"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29707"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43698"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44741"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74866"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of low back pain. He works as a plumber and reports the pain is worse after long periods of bending and lifting at work. He has taken regular paracetamol and ibuprofen with minimal relief. He has reflux and takes omeprazole daily though notes it is always triggered after drinking his two beers each night.  He denies any recreational drugs. He expresses dissatisfaction with his current employment and mentions he is considering a workers\u0027 compensation claim so wants proof that his work is damaging his back. He denies any leg weakness, bladder or bowel changes, trauma, fever or unexplained weight loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. He has paraspinal muscle tenderness and reduced lumbar range of motion due to pain. Straight leg raise is negative bilaterally. Neurological examination of the lower limbs is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Magnetic Resonance Imaging","Lumbar spine X-ray","Bone scan","Computed Tomography scan","No imaging required"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with chronic low back pain with several psychosocial risk factors (orange flags) including heavy manual work, job dissatisfaction, and a potential compensation claim. These factors are associated with poorer outcomes and prolonged disability.  He has a red flag of being over 40 years of age, however does not demonstrate any abnormal neurology, or concerns for abscess, fracture or malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo imaging\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step as there are no concerning features (red flags) such as neurological deficits, cancer risk factors, or signs of infection. Current evidence-based guidelines recommend against routine imaging for low back pain without red flags as it does not improve outcomes and may lead to unnecessary interventions.  The findings on imaging of lower back pain does not always correlate with disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELumbar spine X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as routine imaging in acute or chronic back pain without red flags. X-rays often show age-related changes that correlate poorly with symptoms and may increase patient anxiety.  If his pain is persisting despite conservative management after 4 weeks, an x-ray could be considered in the future.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic Resonance Imaging\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if there were red flags such as progressive neurological deficits, suspected cauda equina syndrome, or concerns about malignancy. These features are not present in this case.  \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed Tomography scan\u003C/strong\u003E would be considered if there were specific concerns about bony pathology or if MRI was contraindicated. However, in this case with no red flags, CT is not indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBone scan\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if there were concerns about infection, malignancy, or occult fracture, none of which are suggested by the history or examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management should focus on addressing workplace ergonomics, maintaining activity within pain limits, massage, heat and exploring psychosocial factors that may be contributing to pain persistence. Early return to work planning and consideration of workplace modifications may be beneficial.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Orange flags in back pain include heavy manual work, job dissatisfaction, and pending compensation claims.","Routine imaging is not indicated for acute low back pain without red flags."],"references":["Parr A, Askin G. Non-radicular low back pain: Assessment and evidence-based treatment.  Australian Journal of General PRactice. 2020: 49 (11).  Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2020/november/non-radicular-low-back-pain","Chou R, Fu R, Carrino J, Deyo R. Imaging strategies for low-back pain: systematic review and meta-analysis.  The Lancet. 2009: 373 (9662).  Available at: https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(09)60172-0/abstract"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60372"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18452"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60372"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T01:54:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T01:55:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11181"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74866"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"45","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.co